if {selected_character} == "celestine":
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/C5S1/c5s1 conrad and mark.mp3" volume=50 bus="Voice"]
	Celestine and Mark arrange items carefully across the stage.
	Celestine: Each case needs to be represented. But not just the crime - the lesson.
	Mark: So how do we show that?
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/C5S1/c5s1 conrad places a piece.mp3" volume=50 bus="Voice"]
	Celestine places a piece of chalk next to a small evidence bag.
	Celestine: For the exam case - chalk and evidence. The lesson was Truth.
	Celestine: Greg cheated, but the evidence revealed the truth. Honesty matters more than success.
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/C5S1/c5s1 he moves to the next position.mp3" volume=50 bus="Voice"]
	She moves to the next position, arranging budget papers in a small maze pattern.
	Celestine: For the missing fund - the maze of choices. The lesson was Responsibility.
	Celestine: Ria made a choice out of desperation, but she had to face the consequences.
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/C5S1/c5s1 mark helps arrange.mp3" volume=50 bus="Voice"]
	Mark helps arrange art supplies next to a photo of a sculpture.
	Mark: The broken sculpture - Creativity. Victor learned that art is about expression, not competition.
	Celestine: Right. And jealousy destroys what it cannot possess.
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/C5S1/c5s1 finally, conrad places.mp3" volume=50 bus="Voice"]
	Finally, Celestine places the old journal carefully on a pedestal.
	Celestine: The journal. Wisdom. Alex learned that knowledge without wisdom causes harm.
	Mark: So what now? We just... wait?
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/C5S1/c5s1 conrad pulls out.mp3" volume=50 bus="Voice"]
	Celestine pulls out a cream-colored card - one she prepared herself, matching B.C.'s style.
	Celestine: I leave this.
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/C5S1/c5s1 he places the card.mp3" volume=50 bus="Voice"]
	She places the card in the center of the arrangement.
	Mark: What does it say?
	Celestine: "Teacher, I've learned your lessons. Each case taught me something about truth, responsibility, creativity, and wisdom. But I still have questions. Will you teach me one more lesson? - C"
	Mark: Simple. Respectful. I like it.
	Celestine: B.C. has always been patient, never forceful. This honors that.
	Celestine: We're not setting a trap. We're extending an invitation.
	Mark: So do we hide and wait to see if they show up?
	Celestine: No. We wait outside. If B.C. wants to meet me, they'll send a signal.
	Celestine: I'll leave the door unlocked. The rest is up to them.
